<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,367,368,394]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Bothrops moojeni</emphasis>
Hoge, 
<number box="[453,512,368,394]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" value="1966.0">1966</number>
</taxonomicName>
“ 
<taxonomicName box="[533,647,368,394]" class="Reptilia" family="Viperidae" genus="Bothrops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="24" pageNumber="93" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="jararaca">Jararaca</taxonomicName>
”
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="24.[151,661,368,427]" box="[151,384,402,427]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">(Figs. 10.4 and 22.4)</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="24.[151,1436,474,679]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">
First record in the Caatinga. This species was recorded only in Bahia and Minas Gerais States. It occurs in altitudes of 
<quantity box="[181,330,510,535]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.35" metricValueMax="6.3" metricValueMin="4.4" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" unit="m" value="535.0" valueMax="630.0" valueMin="440.0">440 to 630 m</quantity>
elevation, close to the Cerrado region, to which the species is considered endemic (Nogueira 
<emphasis box="[1380,1436,510,535]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">et al.</emphasis>
<number box="[151,211,547,571]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" value="2011.0">2011</number>
). It is the most conspicuous and widespread viperid snake of the Cerrado region (
<bibRefCitation author="Melgarejo" box="[1112,1295,546,571]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" refString="Melgarejo, A. (2003) Serpentes peconhentas do Brasil. In: Cardoso, J. L. C., Franca, F. O. S., Fan, H. W., Malaque, C. M. S. &amp; Haddad, J. R. (Eds.), Animais peconhentos no Brasil. Sarvier, Sao Paulo, pp. 33 - 61." type="book chapter" year="2003">
Melgarejo 
<number box="[1236,1295,547,571]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" value="2003.0">2003</number>
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Nogueira" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" refString="Nogueira, C., Sawaya, R. J. &amp; Martins, M. (2003) Ecology of the pitviper, Bothrops moojeni, in the Brazilian Cerrado. Journal of Herpetology, 37, 653 - 659. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1670 / 120 - 02 A" type="journal article" year="2003">
Nogueira 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">et al.</emphasis>
<number box="[186,247,583,607]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" value="2003.0">2003</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). It is typical of gallery forests or adjacent riparian habitats in the Cerrado region (
<bibRefCitation author="Nogueira" box="[1164,1401,582,607]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" refString="Nogueira, C., Sawaya, R. J. &amp; Martins, M. (2003) Ecology of the pitviper, Bothrops moojeni, in the Brazilian Cerrado. Journal of Herpetology, 37, 653 - 659. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1670 / 120 - 02 A" type="journal article" year="2003">
Nogueira 
<emphasis box="[1277,1326,582,607]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">et al</emphasis>
. 
<number box="[1340,1401,583,607]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" value="2003.0">2003</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). It has terrestrial habits, is nocturnal, and is a generalist feeder on vertebrate prey (Martins 
<emphasis box="[1135,1184,618,643]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">et al</emphasis>
. 
<number box="[1198,1257,619,643]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" value="2002.0">2002</number>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Nogueira" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" refString="Nogueira, C., Sawaya, R. J. &amp; Martins, M. (2003) Ecology of the pitviper, Bothrops moojeni, in the Brazilian Cerrado. Journal of Herpetology, 37, 653 - 659. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1670 / 120 - 02 A" type="journal article" year="2003">
Nogueira 
<emphasis box="[1380,1429,618,643]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">et al</emphasis>
. 
<number box="[151,212,655,679]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" value="2003.0">2003</number>
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
